Lower Back Pain¶

About 80 percent of adults experience low back pain at some point in their lifetimes. It is the most common cause of job-related disability and a leading contributor to missed work days. In a large survey, more than a quarter of adults reported experiencing low back pain during the past 3 months [1]

It can be caused by a variety of problems with any parts of the complex, interconnected network of spinal muscles, nerves, bones, discs or tendons in the lumbar spine.

While lower back pain is extremely common, the symptoms and severity of lower back pain vary greatly. A simple lower back muscle strain might be excruciating enough to necessitate an emergency room visit, while a degenerating disc might cause only mild, intermittent discomfort.

Typical sources of low back pain include:

  • The large nerve roots in the low back that go to the legs may be irritated.
  • The smaller nerves that supply the low back may be irritated.
  • The large paired lower back muscles (erector spinae) may be strained.
  • The bones, ligaments or joints may be damaged.
  • An intervertebral disc may be degenerating.

Goal of the exercise¶

Identify if a person suffers from abnormal or normal lower back pain using collected physical spine details/data.

Dataset:

https://www.kaggle.com/sammy123/lower-back-pain-symptoms-dataset/

Perform a normality test to find if the data follows a normal distribution:

Kolmogorov-Smirnov test performs a test of the distribution G(x) of an observed random variable against a given distribution F(x).

Under the null hypothesis the two distributions are identical, G(x)=F(x).

The KS test is only valid for continuous distributions.

In [30]:
# create a function to evaluate normality
from colorama import Fore
from scipy.stats import kstest # Kstest

def ks_test(data):
    """Perform the Kolmogorov-Smirnov test for goodness of fit"""
    
    stat, p = kstest(data, 'norm')
    assert(not np.isnan(stat) and not np.isnan(p))
    print('Statistics=%.3f, p=%.3f' % (stat, p))
    
    # interpret
    alpha = 0.05
    if p > alpha:
        print(Fore.BLUE, '+ Sample DOES LOOK Gaussian (fail to reject H0)')
    else:
        print(Fore.RED, '- Sample DOES NOT look Gaussian (reject H0)')
    print(Fore.RESET)

Before training certain algorithms the data should be scaled.

MinMax scaler transforms features by scaling each feature to a given range.

This estimator scales and translates each feature individually such that it is in the given range on the training set, e.g. between zero and one.

We are going to scale the data, evaluate normality, and transform the non-normal distributions before training the algorithm.

from sklearn.preprocessing import MinMaxScaler

# this is to avoid NaNs and np.inf when tranforming the data after scaling
# the data is transformed so it then follows a normal distribution

Transform the data so it follows a normal distribution:

Apply a power transform featurewise to make data more Gaussian-like.

Power transforms are a family of parametric, monotonic transformations that are applied to make data more Gaussian-like.

PowerTransformer supports the Box-Cox transform and the Yeo-Johnson transform.

Box-Cox requires input data to be strictly positive, while Yeo-Johnson supports both positive or negative data.

By default, zero-mean, unit-variance normalization is applied to the transformed data.

In [43]:
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV

clf = LogisticRegression(class_weight='balanced', random_state=42)
param_grid = [{'C': [0.1, 1, 10, 100, 1000],
               'solver' :['newton-cg', 'lbfgs', 'liblinear', 'sag', 'saga']}]
